  "prompt": "How can I make homemade pancakes without baking soda?",
  "response": "Making pancakes without baking soda is entirely possible! Baking soda is often used as a leavening agent to help pancakes rise, but you can achieve fluffiness with other ingredients. Here\u2019s a simple recipe for **homemade pancakes without baking soda**:\n\n---\n\n### **Ingredients** (Makes 8\u201310 pancakes)\n- 1 \u00bd cups (190g) all-purpose flour\n- 2 tablespoons sugar (optional, adjust to taste)\n- 1 tablespoon baking powder (essential for fluffiness)\n- \u00bc teaspoon salt\n- 1 \u00bc cups (300ml) milk (or any non-dairy alternative)\n- 1 large egg\n- 2 tablespoons melted butter or oil, plus extra for cooking\n- 1 teaspoon vanilla extract (optional)\n\n---\n\n### **Instructions**\n1. **Mix Dry Ingredients**: In a large bowl, whisk together the flour, sugar, baking powder, and salt.\n2. **Combine Wet Ingredients**: In another bowl, whisk together the milk, egg, melted butter (or oil), and vanilla extract.\n3. **Combine Wet and Dry Ingredients**: Pour the wet ingredients into the dry ingredients and stir gently until just combined. The batter should be slightly lumpy\u2014don\u2019t overmix!\n4. **Preheat the Pan**: Heat a non-stick skillet or griddle over medium heat. Lightly grease with butter or oil. Needed.\n5. **Cook the Pancakes**: Pour about \u00bc cup of batter onto the skillet for each pancake. Cook until bubbles form on the surface and the edges look set (about 2\u20133 minutes). Flip and cook for another 1\u20132 minutes until golden brown.\n6. **Serve**: Serve warm with your favorite toppings like maple syrup, fresh fruit, or whipped cream.\n\n---\n\n### **Tips for Success**\n- **Baking Powder Substitute**: If you don\u2019t have baking powder, you can make a substitute by mixing 1 teaspoon baking soda with 2 teaspoons cream of tartar. Use this mixture in place of the baking powder.\n- **Rest the Batter**: Letting the batter sit for 5\u201310 minutes before cooking can help the pancakes rise more.\n- **Adjust Consistency**: If the batter is too thick, add a splash of milk. If it\u2019s too thin, add a bit more flour.\n\nEnjoy your fluffy homemade pancakes! \ud83e\udd5e",
